      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Our research has yielded promising results in the development of drought-resistant maize strains. Specifically, Strain A demonstrated a 15.0% increase in yield under water stress, with a 13.5% increase in dry biomass and a 1.5% increase in kernel yield. Furthermore, Strain B exhibited a 22.0% survival rate in extreme drought conditions, with 21.8% of plants surviving for 30 days without irrigation. Additionally, our findings indicate that soil moisture retention improved by 10.0% across all test plots, with an average water retention capacity of 105.6 ml/g of soil.\n\nThese results demonstrate the potential of our drought-resistant maize strains to address the pressing issue of water scarcity in agriculture. By incorporating these strains into farming practices, we anticipate significant improvements in crop yields and resilience to drought conditions. Our research provides a foundation for further investigation into the genetic and physiological mechanisms underlying these traits, with the ultimate goal of developing more effective and sustainable agricultural solutions.",
